Buying stiff shoes will prevent your toddler from being able to bend their feet and is not healthy or comfortable. Also keep in mind that arch support isn't necessary since toddlers will usually outgrow shoes before they are able to wear out the soles. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6b/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/6b/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Choose shoes with a large width. Your toddler's bones are softest before the age of 4, so wide shoes will allow room for their feet to develop properly. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/b4/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Select shoes made of porous, breathable material such as canvas, cloth or leather. Not only are these shoes more flexible, but they will also allow the air to circulate around your toddler's feet. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-459px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/23/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet3.jpg/v4-759px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Look for shoes with good tread and avoid shoes with slick or smooth treads to prevent your toddler from falling, slipping and sliding. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-459px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e2/Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet4.jpg/v4-759px-Measure-a-Toddler-for-Shoes-Step-5Bullet4.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":306,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":506.31868131868134,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
